{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> πίθος</b> [ῐ], ὁ, <br /> <b>large wine-jar</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 24.527, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 2.340, 23.305, 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 98, 368, “IG” 12.328.2, etc.: usually of earthenware, π. κεράμινοι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.96, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Pax” 703, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Laches” 187b, “Grg.” 493a \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; π. ἀργύρεοι, sent by Croesus to Delphi, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.51 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; but π. ξύλινοι <b>casks</b>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 5.1.12, compare 2nd c.AD: Herodianus Grammaticus 8.4.5. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> proverbial, εἰς τὸν τετρημένον π. ἀντλεῖν, of the task of the Danaids, i.e. of labour in vain, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Oeconomicus” 7.40, compare {5-6th c.BC}: Philetaerus Comicus 18.5, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Herm.” 61, “DMort.” 11.4 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; applied to insatiable appetites, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 493b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; to largesses made by demagogues, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Politica” 1320a32, compare “Oec.” 1344b25 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; ἐκ πίθω ἀντλεῖς you have wine by the <b>cask</b>ful, i.e. your purse is deep, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 3rd c.BC: Theocritus Poeta Bucolicus 10.13 \">Refs 3rd c.BC+</a>]; ἐν πίθῳ ἡ κεραμεία γιγνομένη 'trying to run before you can walk', [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Laches” 187b, compare “Grg.” 514e, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 469 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ζωὴ πίθου a Cynic's life, like that of Diogenes, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd c.AD: Zenobius Paroemiographus 4.14 \">Refs 2nd c.AD+</a>]; π. φρενῶν <b>a cask full of</b> wit, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-3rd c.BC: Menander Comicus “Μονόστιχοι - Fragmenta Comicorum Graecorum” 240 (= “IG” 14.699), explained with reference to Diogenes by 12th c.AD: Eustathius Episcopus Thessalonicensis 1363.40. \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> ={πιθίας}, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Mundo” 395b12, 2nd c.AD: Ptolemaeus Mathematicus “Tetrabiblos” 90 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]. (Cf. Latin <i>fidelia.</i>)","strongNumber":"G8792","accentedUnicode":"πίθος","shortDef":"a cask","mediumDef":"a cask","stepGloss":"a cask","stepTransliteration":"pithos","count":0,"_step_Type":"word"}]}